Using remote sensing to map invasive species

Success in the strategies to manage biological invasions relies on the ability to detect and monitor species distributions. However, field surveys devoted to detect and map invasive species are time consuming and might lead to observational bias, e.g. decreased sampling effort at less accesible areas.

Remote sensing provides a large-scale standardized spatially and temporally explicit data to map and monitor the distribution of invasive species. Here, as part of the DIARS project, we present a method to map invasive species using hyperspectral images.

The dataset

In this tutorial we will map the distribution of X species in an already prepared artificial image (you can download it from HERE). These dataset includes: the hyperspectral image (tif file) and a set of calibration, validation and background points containing ground measurements that will be use to develop the species distribution map.

The method

Setting the R environment

Lets start by loading the libraries that we are going to be using in this tutorial. TO load the packages, it is necessary to first install them using the command install.packages(c("raster","rgdal","hyperSpec","rgeos","rgrass7")).

library(raster)
library(rgdal)
library(hyperSpec)
library(rgeos)
library(rgrass7)

It is recommended to first create a folder where the datasets (tif file and point files, download a sample dataset from HERE) are located and the outputs and results will be saved. To set the working directory in R to the folder created:

setwd("/home/garzonc/Desktop/DIARS")

Load the hyperspectral image in R and plot it using one of the bands

filelist <- dir(pattern = ".tiff")
mos <- raster(filelist[2], band = 150)
plot(mos)

Is important to also extract the values for an area around the point (buffer area), in this case of the size of the field plots. So we have to create a buffer around calibration points and save it as a shapefile:

dataBuffer <- gBuffer(pointdata_cal, byid = T, width = 3, capStyle = "SQUARE")

plot(mos)
points(pointdata_cal, pch = 3, cex = 0.3)
plot(dataBuffer, add = TRUE)

# shapefile(dataBuffer, 'CalibBuffer3m.shp', overwrite=TRUE)

Create a table with only the coordinates (x,y)

pointdataXY_calB <- pointdata_cal@data[, 3:4]

Write the function to calculate the mean for each buffer area:

weightmean <- function(x) {
    sum(x[, 1] * x[, 2])
}

And extract and calculate the value in each area and for each band:

for (i in 1:248) {
    mos <- raster(filelist[2], band = i)
    pixvals <- extract(mos, dataBuffer, method = "simple", small = T, weights = T)
    pixmean <- sapply(pixvals, weightmean)
    pointdataXY_calB <- cbind(pointdataXY_calB, pixmean)
}

Once the loop is finished, add the category column and joint the coordinates, column and row names to the dataframe with the values extracted for each band. Preview the resulting table and save it as a csv file.

specBuffer <- cbind(rep("Calibration", 90), pointdataXY_calB)

type <- rep("Calibration", 90)
bands <- c(1:248)
CalibBuffer <- cbind(type, pointdataXY_calB)
colnames(CalibBuffer) <- c("type", "x", "y", bands)
rownames(CalibBuffer) <- pointdata_calB@data$cat
head(CalibBuffer)  #Run this line to preview the first 5 rows of the table
write.table(CalibBuffer, "CalibBuffer.csv", quote = F)

Spectral bands analysis and selection via Principal Components Analysis (PCA)

Hyperspectral images provide mayne advantages due to the large amount of information contain in each pixel (in this case 248 bands) but this also posits limitations in time and processing power. One of the techniques most commonly used to reduce the dimension of the data, without loosing relevant information, is the Principal Components Analysis (PCA).

library(raster)
library(rgdal)
library(foreach)

Points..

plots <- read.table("CalibBuffer.csv", header = T, sep = " ")[, -c(2:3)]
Background <- read.table("PointBackground.csv", header = T, sep = " ")[, -c(2:3)]


spec <- rbind(plots, Background)

library(reshape2)
library(ggplot2)
sample <- melt(spec, id = c("type"))

p <- ggplot(sample, aes(sample[, 2], sample[, 3])) + geom_boxplot(aes(fill = sample[, 
    2]), outlier.colour = NULL) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, 
    hjust = 0), axis.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14), title = element_text(face = "bold", 
    size = 16), legend.position = "none") + labs(title = paste("Spectral response"), 
    x = "Wavelength, nm", y = "Response")
p

Calculate first component

plots <- as.matrix(read.table("CalibBuffer.csv", header = T, sep = " ")[, -c(1:3)])
Background <- as.matrix(read.table("PointBackground.csv", header = T, sep = " ")[, 
    -c(1:3)])


spec1 <- rbind(plots, Background)

pca <- prcomp(spec1, scale. = T, center = T)

pca_red <- prcomp(spec1, scale. = T, center = T, tol = 0.01)  # Calculate only first components, tol=0 or tol = 
pca_red$sdev[1:11]

Mapping current species distribution with Maxent

Before starting running any script, it is important to download Maxent from the website https://www.cs.princeton.edu/~schapire/maxent/) and copy the file maxent.jarand paste it in the folder called java of the dismo package file.

library(dismo)
library(rJava)

setwd("/home/garzonc/Desktop/DIARS")

Load the tables with the previously extracted values for the buffer areas around the calibration points, and used the vector cal_points to select the plots with >0 species coverage values (cam_cover column). Joint the presences table with the background table, and in the resulting table omit the x and y coordinate and type columns and only keep the spectral values. Finally create a vector y with 1 and 0 values corresponding to the presences (1) and background (0) rows.

occs <- read.table("CalibBuffer.csv", header = T, sep = " ")
pointdata <- readVECT("cal_pointsDataset")
## Exporting 90 features...
##    5%  11%  17%  23%  30%  36%  42%  48%  54%  60%  66%  72%  78%  84%  90%  96% 100%
## v.out.ogr complete. 90 features (Point type) written to <cal_pointsDataset>
## (SQLite format).
## OGR data source with driver: SQLite 
## Source: "/home/garzonc/Documents/grassData/DIARS/PERMANENT/.tmp/edysan2.sante.rech.u-picardie.fr/726.0", layer: "cal_pointsDataset"
## with 90 features
## It has 5 fields
occsALL <- cbind(pointdata@data, occs)
occsPRES <- subset(occsALL, occsALL$cam_cover > 0)
occsPRES <- occsPRES[, -c(1:5)]
Background <- read.table("PointBackground.csv", header = T, sep = " ")
names(occsPRES) <- names(Background)
specs <- rbind(occsPRES, Background)
specs <- specs[, -c(1:3)]
specs <- specs[, -c(1, 2, 146:157, 194:220)]
y <- c(rep(1, nrow(occsPRES)), rep(0, nrow(Background)))

After preparing the data tables you can run the model, generate the predictions and the probabilities map.

library(dismo)
me <- maxent(specs, y, args = c("addsamplestobackground=true", "applyThresholdRule=10 percentile training presence"), 
    path = "./outputR")

layers <- stack(list.files(".", "asc", full.names = TRUE))
pred <- predict(me, layers, progress = "text")
## 
  |                                                                       
  |                                                                 |   0%
  |                                                                       
  |================                                                 |  25%
  |                                                                       
  |================================                                 |  50%
  |                                                                       
  |=================================================                |  75%
  |                                                                       
  |=================================================================| 100%
## 
plot(pred)

writeRaster(pred, "./outputR/map.tif", overwrite = T)
save(me, file = "./outputR/mx_obj.RData")
You can explore the AUC curve and values from the maxent model by opening the html file stored in the ./outputR1 folder.

The validation table just created is used in the evaluate function to evaluate the model previously constructed. The resulting evaluation contains the outcomes of the model cross-validation, such as the True Skill Statistic (TSS) and ROC curves. Additionally, the threshold function allows selection the threshold value where the sum of the sensitivity and specificity values is the highest. This value can also be used to generate the presence map based on the model prediction.

e <- evaluate(model = me, p = occsP, a = occsA)
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
tss <- e@TPR + e@TNR - 1
plot(e@t, tss, type = "l", xlab = "Thresholds", ylab = "TSS", main = "TSS")
e@t[which.max(tss)]
## [1] 0.1234042
plot(e, "ROC")

# Presence map based on the threshold value
par(mfrow = c(1, 1))
tr <- threshold(e, "spec_sens")
plot(pred > tr, main = "Presence Locations and Prediction (Reduced Model)")

# See all the outcomes of the model evaluation
str(e)
